# Section (United States land surveying)

A [section](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Section_(United_States_land_surveying)) in the context of [United States land surveying](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_land_surveying) is a fundamental unit of land area, a precisely defined parcel that forms the backbone of the vast [Public Land Survey System](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_Land_Survey_System) (PLSS). This system, meticulously established in the wake of the [American Revolutionary War](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Revolutionary_War), was designed to facilitate the orderly division and sale of the rapidly expanding [federal lands](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federal_lands) of the [United States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States). The section, a square parcel measuring one statute mile on each side and encompassing 640 [acres](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acre) (approximately 2.6 [square kilometers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_kilometer)), is the cornerstone of this monumental undertaking. Its consistent dimensions and hierarchical subdivision have provided a standardized framework for property ownership, resource management, and infrastructure development across much of the nation, from the [Great Plains](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Plains) to the [Rocky Mountains](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rocky_Mountains) and beyond.

The establishment of the section as a land measurement unit is inextricably linked to the [Land Ordinance of 1785](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_Ordinance_of_1785), a landmark piece of legislation that sought to bring order to the chaotic process of surveying and distributing western territories. Prior to this ordinance, land claims were often ambiguous, leading to disputes and hindering effective governance. The PLSS, with its systematic grid of townships and sections, was a revolutionary solution, providing a clear and unambiguous method for defining land boundaries. Each section, a mile square, was further divided into smaller, more manageable units, most notably quarter sections of 160 acres, a size that became historically significant as the amount of land a [homesteader](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homesteader) could claim under the [Homestead Act of 1862](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homestead_Act_of_1862). This tiered system of division allowed for both large-scale land allocation and smaller, individual land ownership, catering to a wide range of economic and social needs.

## System of Survey

The PLSS operates on a rectilinear grid system, a stark contrast to the more irregular metes and bounds system prevalent in the original thirteen colonies. This grid is anchored by a [Principal Meridian](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_Meridian) and a [Base Line](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_Line), which serve as the primary reference lines for the entire survey area. From these meridians and base lines, the land is systematically divided into [townships](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Township_(United_States)), each measuring six miles square. A township is a fundamental unit within the PLSS, containing 36 sections. These townships are arranged in rows, known as “ranges,” running east and west of the Principal Meridian, and in columns, known as “tiers,” running north and south of the Base Line. The numbering of townships and ranges originates from the intersection of the Principal Meridian and Base Line, creating a unique identifier for each township based on its position relative to these axes. For instance, a township might be designated as Township 3 North, Range 5 West, indicating its location three tiers north and five ranges west of the initial intersection.

Within each township, the 36 sections are numbered in a specific, serpentine pattern, starting with Section 1 in the northeast corner and progressing westward, then southward, and then eastward again, finally ending with Section 36 in the southeast corner. This numbering convention, while seemingly arbitrary, ensures that each section within a township has a distinct designation. The section itself, as previously mentioned, is a square mile, comprising 640 acres. This square mile is then typically subdivided into four quarter sections, each measuring 160 acres. These quarter sections, in turn, can be further divided into quarter-quarter sections of 40 acres, and sometimes even further into 10-acre parcels, although such fine divisions were less common in the initial surveys. The regularity and mathematical precision of this system were revolutionary for its time, enabling efficient land management and settlement. It’s a system built on straight lines and right angles, a starkly rational approach to the wild, untamed lands of the frontier.

## History

The genesis of the section as a unit of land measurement is deeply rooted in the evolving needs of the nascent [United States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States). Following the [Revolutionary War](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Revolutionary_War), the federal government found itself in possession of vast tracts of western territory, acquired through treaties and territorial cessions from states like [Virginia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virginia) and [North Carolina](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Carolina). The challenge was how to manage, survey, and sell these lands to generate revenue and encourage westward expansion. The existing land division methods, primarily the [metes and bounds](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metes_and_bounds) system used in the original colonies, were complex, often based on natural landmarks and subjective descriptions, leading to frequent boundary disputes and title uncertainties.

The [Land Ordinance of 1785](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_Ordinance_of_1785) was a direct response to this challenge. It mandated the rectangular survey system, establishing the township as the basic unit of land division, with each township to be six miles square. Within each township, the land was to be divided into 36 sections, each one mile square and containing 640 acres. This ordinance laid the groundwork for the [Public Land Survey System](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_Land_Survey_System) (PLSS), which would become the dominant method for surveying and describing land in the United States. The system was designed to be systematic, orderly, and easily understandable, facilitating land sales and preventing the kind of confusion that plagued earlier land distribution efforts. The section, in its standardized 640-acre form, became the building block of this new survey system, a testament to the desire for order and efficiency in the management of public lands.

Subsequent legislation, most notably the [Homestead Act of 1862](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homestead_Act_of_1862), further solidified the importance of the section. This act allowed any [citizen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Citizen) or intended citizen to claim 160 acres of surveyed government land, provided they lived on it, improved it, and paid a nominal filing fee. The 160-acre parcel, a quarter section, became the iconic unit of the [American frontier](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_frontier), shaping the dreams and realities of countless settlers. The PLSS, with its precisely defined sections and quarter sections, provided the framework for this massive land distribution, allowing for the rapid settlement and development of the western United States. The surveys were conducted by surveyors employed by the [General Land Office](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Land_Office) (GLO), later absorbed into the [Bureau of Land Management](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bureau_of_Land_Management), who followed strict guidelines to establish boundary markers, often [monuments](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monument) of stone or wood, and recorded their findings in detailed field notes and plats. These records remain invaluable historical and legal documents today.

## Legal Description

In the realm of [real property law](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_property_law) in the United States, the section serves as a crucial element in the legal description of land parcels. The PLSS provides a standardized and unambiguous method for identifying and locating real estate, a stark contrast to the often-problematic metes and bounds descriptions that rely on distances, directions, and natural or artificial landmarks. A legal description based on the PLSS typically follows a hierarchical structure, beginning with the smallest subdivision and progressing to the larger encompassing units. For example, a description might read "the Northwest quarter of the Southwest quarter of Section 15, Township 2 North, Range 3 East of the Fourth Principal Meridian." This detailed breakdown precisely identifies a 40-acre parcel of land.

The components of this legal description are critical:

*   **Quarter-Quarter Section:** This specifies the smallest described portion of the section. In the example, it's the Northwest quarter of the Southwest quarter, which would be a 40-acre parcel (1/4 of 1/4 of 640 acres).
*   **Section Number:** This identifies the specific one-mile-square parcel within the township. In the example, it's Section 15.
*   **Township Designation:** This indicates the township's position relative to the Base Line and Principal Meridian. The example specifies Township 2 North (meaning two tiers north of the Base Line) and Range 3 East (meaning three ranges east of the Principal Meridian).
*   **Principal Meridian:** This is the primary north-south reference line for the survey area. The example specifies the Fourth Principal Meridian, a distinct line established for a particular region.

This systematic approach ensures that each described parcel is unique and can be precisely located on the ground. The section, therefore, acts as a foundational element, a known quantity within the larger grid, allowing for the clear and irrefutable identification of property boundaries. The accuracy of the original surveys, while generally high for their time, is not infallible, and discrepancies can arise due to errors in measurement, the curvature of the [Earth](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth), or natural [geological](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geology) changes over time. However, the legal framework established by the PLSS, with the section at its heart, has proven remarkably robust in defining land ownership for centuries. When disputes arise, surveyors often rely on original survey markers and established rules of boundary retracement to resolve them.

## Size and Subdivision

The standard section in the United States land survey system is defined as a square parcel measuring exactly one statute mile on each side. This results in an area of 640 acres. This precise measurement is a testament to the systematic nature of the [Public Land Survey System](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_Land_Survey_System) (PLSS), which aimed for uniformity and predictability in land division. The mile-square section was a practical unit, large enough to be economically significant but small enough to be surveyed and managed with the technology available at the time.

The subdivision of a section is equally standardized, forming a hierarchical structure that allows for parcels of various sizes. The most common subdivision is into four [quarter sections](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quarter_section), each containing 160 acres. These quarter sections are created by dividing the section along lines running north-south and east-west through its center. Each quarter section is then a square parcel measuring half a mile on each side.

Further subdivision typically occurs into quarter-quarter sections, each containing 40 acres. These are created by dividing each quarter section into four equal parts. A quarter-quarter section is a square parcel measuring a quarter mile on each side. This 40-acre parcel became particularly significant due to its association with the [Homestead Act of 1862](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homestead_Act_of_1862), which granted settlers 160 acres (a quarter section).

In some cases, particularly in areas with high land values or specific agricultural needs, sections could be further divided into 10-acre parcels, which would be quarter-quarter-quarter sections. These divisions are achieved by bisecting the 40-acre parcels. The smallest commonly recognized subdivision within the PLSS is therefore the 10-acre parcel, though the 40-acre and 160-acre parcels remain the most frequently encountered in legal descriptions and property records. The consistency of these subdivisions is crucial for maintaining clarity in land ownership and transfer across vast expanses of the country. It’s a system that, despite its age, continues to function with remarkable efficiency, a testament to the foresight of its creators.